		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2024 SI"></a><br><code>sle2024s/paper08</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Spectrum-based rule- and item-level localization of faults in context-free grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MoeketsiRaselimo.html">Moeketsi Raselimo</a>, <a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jss.2024.112067">10.1016/j.jss.2024.112067</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="../sle2019/paper02.html"><em>Spectrum-based fault localization for context-free grammars</em></a> (SLE 2019)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The main goal is diagnosing faults in language definitions (context-free grammars) by ranking suspicious rules/items using collected “grammar spectra.”
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagL">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> The method is spectrum-based fault localization driven by test suites and instrumented/synthesized parsing runs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The approach is evaluated at scale on seeded-fault grammars across parsers/test suites/ranking metrics, reporting localization effectiveness.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
	</body>
